trip:
  name: Japan — May to July 2026
  author: Bruna Sanches Caricati & Renan Cammarosano de Lima
  duration: 59 nights
  tags: [japan, asia, first-time, culture, history, food, onsen, temples]
  info:
  - ANA-reservation: F7ZHBA
  - ANA-ticket: 2052429593670-671
  note: |
    A two-month journey through Japan — Tokyo, Hakone, Osaka, Hiroshima,
    Kyoto, and back to Tokyo. First visit for both. Focus on history, culture,
    and authentic food. No seafood preference — prioritise meat, tofu, and
    vegetable options when ordering.

    **Rainy season (tsuyu) warning:** Most of the long Tokyo stay (June 6 –
    July 3) falls inside Japan's rainy season. Expect intermittent showers
    and high humidity (22–28C / 70–90% humidity). It does not rain all day —
    roughly 40–50% chance on any given day. Plan outdoor activities for
    mornings; keep museums and indoor experiences for afternoons.
    Rainy Kyoto temples and gardens are often the most atmospheric.

    **Grutto Pass:** Buy on arrival in Tokyo long stay (June 6, from any
    participating venue). Valid for 2 months at 107 museums, gardens, and
    zoos. Essential for the 27-night Tokyo stay. Cost: 2,500 yen.

    **Luggage forwarding (TA-Q-BIN):** Use Yamato Transport's luggage
    forwarding service between every hotel change. Send bags the night
    before you travel — they arrive the next day (1,500–2,500 yen per bag).
    Eliminates hauling suitcases through train stations entirely.

    **Apps to install before departure:**
    Suica (Apple Pay / IC card), Google Maps offline, Tabelog (restaurants),
    Smart EX (Shinkansen bookings), Visit Japan Web (immigration forms),
    EMot (Hakone Freepass and Romancecar tickets already here),
    GetYourGuide (Skytree and teamLab tickets live here).

    **Money:** Withdraw yen at 7-Eleven or Japan Post ATMs — most reliable
    for foreign cards. Many small restaurants and neighbourhood shops are
    still cash-only. Start with 30,000–50,000 yen in cash on arrival.

    **JR Pass:** Not recommended for this trip. Only 5 major Shinkansen
    legs total. Individual tickets via Smart EX are significantly cheaper.

itinerary:

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # OUTBOUND FLIGHTS
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- flight:
    from:
      name: Palma de Mallorca Airport (PMI)
      lat: 39.5517
      lng: 2.7388
    to:
      name: Zurich Airport (ZRH)
      lat: 47.4647
      lng: 8.5492
    departs: 2026-05-04T08:20
    arrives: 2026-05-04T10:15
    info:
    - operator: Eurowings
    - flight: EW6836
    - seat: 20B
    - class: W
    - reservation: F7ZHBA

- flight:
    from:
      name: Zurich Airport (ZRH)
    to:
      name: Tokyo Narita International Airport (NRT)
      lat: 35.7647
      lng: 140.3864
    departs: 2026-05-04T13:05
    arrives: 2026-05-05T09:10
    info:
    - operator: ANA (operated by Swiss)
    - flight: NH6752
    - class: Q
    - reservation: F7ZHBA
    note: |
      Fill in Visit Japan Web forms before landing to speed through
      immigration. Try to sleep on the plane — Japan is 7 time zones
      ahead of Spain.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # TOKYO — WEEK ONE (7 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Tokyo:
    arrives: 2026-05-05
    departs: 2026-05-12
    duration: 7 nights
    location: Tokyo, Japan
    stay:
    - Sakura Hotel Nippori:
        arrives: 2026-05-05T15:00
        departs: 2026-05-12T11:00
        location:
          address: Sendagi 3-43-15, Bunkyo Ward, Tokyo 113-0022, Japan
          lat: 35.7283
          lng: 139.7614
        info:
        - confirmation: "5531.957.709"
        - pin: "4587"
        - phone: +81 3 5685 1200
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Japanese-Style Room with Shared Bathroom (futon, tatami)
        - cancellation: free until May 3
        - price: approx. 84,823 yen — pay at property
        note: |
          Yanaka-Sendagi is one of Tokyo's best-preserved old
          neighbourhoods. From Narita take the Keisei Skyliner to
          Nippori Station (41 min, 2,570 yen) — direct and easiest.
          Purchase a Suica card at the airport before boarding.

    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival day — Yanaka neighbourhood
        time: 2026-05-05
        status: done
        note: |
          Yanaka Cemetery, Yanaka Ginza, Nezu Shrine. Dinner at a nearby
          okonomiyaki restaurant.
    - day:
        title: Tsukiji, water bus to Asakusa, Kappabashi
        time: 2026-05-06
        status: done
        note: |
          Tsukiji Outer Market for breakfast, then Hamarikyu Gardens and
          the Tokyo Water Bus up the Sumida River to Asakusa. Senso-ji,
          Asakusa Shrine, Kappabashi, and Hoppy Street in the afternoon.
          No dinner — skipped after a full day.
        items:
        - Tsukiji Outer Market:
            time: 8am
            duration: 1h30m
            priority: must
            tags: [market, food, cultural]
            location:
              name: Tsukiji Outer Market
              lat: 35.6654
              lng: 139.7707
            note: |
              The working outer ring of what was once the world's
              largest fish market — dozens of vendors sell fresh
              produce, street food, and specialist ingredients every
              morning. Have breakfast here: tamagoyaki (thick sweet-
              savoury rolled omelette) cut to order at the egg stalls,
              dashimaki sandwiches, fresh fruit on a stick, sesame
              tofu. The egg stalls are exceptional even if you skip
              the seafood counters.

              **Cultural note:** The inner wholesale market moved to Toyosu in 2018,
              but the outer vendors — many from families operating
              the same stall for four or five generations — remained.
              The market's vendors traditionally supplied Tokyo's
              restaurant industry; this outer ring was always the
              public-facing half, selling surplus and prepared foods
              while the inner market handled wholesale tonnage.
        - Hamarikyu Gardens:
            time: 9:45am
            duration: 45m
            tags: [garden, nature, Edo period]
            location:
              name: Hamarikyu Gardens
              lat: 35.6601
              lng: 139.7634
            note: |
              A tidal garden on the bay shore, 10 minutes' walk from
              Tsukiji. Once a Tokugawa shogunate hunting ground and
              duck reserve — the tidal pond connects directly to Tokyo
              Bay, rising and falling with the tides. One of the only
              Edo-period daimyo gardens still intact in the city.
              The water bus pier is inside the garden — buy your ticket
              at the pier before boarding.
        - Tokyo Water Bus — Hamarikyu to Asakusa:
            time: 10:40am
            duration: 40m
            priority: must
            tags: [boat, river, experience, transport]
            location:
              name: Hamarikyu Pier (Suijo Bus)
              lat: 35.6606
              lng: 139.7634
            note: |
              A low, flat riverboat that runs up the Sumida River from
              Hamarikyu to Asakusa Pier — passing under 12 bridges,
              past the old waterfront warehouses, and through the heart
              of the city at water level. Book at the pier (no advance
              reservation needed) or via Tokyo Cruise website.

              **Cultural note:** The Sumida River was Tokyo's highway for 400 years —
              rice, timber, goods, and people all moved this way. The
              great shitamachi (old downtown) neighbourhoods of Asakusa,
              Nihonbashi, and Fukagawa were built on its banks because
              of river access, not in spite of it. Arriving at Asakusa
              by river is not a tourist gimmick — it's the historically
              correct approach. The view of the Skytree rising above
              the old boathouses as you round the final bend is one
              of Tokyo's best.
        - Senso-ji Temple:
            time: 11:30am
            duration: 1h30m
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, cultural, landmark]
            location:
              name: Senso-ji Temple
              lat: 35.7148
              lng: 139.7967
            note: |
              Tokyo's oldest and most visited temple — anchored by the
              great Kaminarimon (Thunder Gate) with its 700kg paper
              lantern, and the Nakamise-dori shopping street leading
              to the five-story pagoda and main hall. Explore the side
              streets off Nakamise rather than walking straight through
              — the alleys on either side have genuinely traditional
              shops. The Denbo-in garden behind the main hall is a
              hidden gem when open.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 645 AD — predating the city of Tokyo by
              a thousand years. The object of worship, a golden image
              of Kannon (goddess of mercy), was reputedly pulled from
              the Sumida River by two fishermen. It has never been
              shown publicly and reportedly never will be — making
              this the most visited temple in the world for something
              no one has ever seen.
        - Asakusa Shrine (Asakusa Jinja):
            time: 1pm
            duration: 20m
            tags: [shrine, hidden gem, cultural]
            location:
              name: Asakusa Shrine
              lat: 35.7153
              lng: 139.7966
            note: |
              A Shinto shrine hidden directly behind Senso-ji's main
              hall — most visitors walk past the gate without noticing
              it exists. Step through the wooden gate and the crowds
              disappear entirely.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 628 AD — older than Senso-ji itself.
              Dedicated to the three men connected to Senso-ji's
              origin: the two fishermen who pulled the Kannon image
              from the Sumida River, and the village headman who
              enshrined it. While Senso-ji honours the goddess they
              found, this shrine honours the ordinary people who found
              her. The contrast in atmosphere — packed temple versus
              quiet shrine 30 metres apart — is one of the most
              striking things in Asakusa.
        - Kappabashi Kitchenware Street:
            time: 1:30pm
            duration: 1h
            tags: [shopping, cultural, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Kappabashi-dori, Taito-ku
              lat: 35.7152
              lng: 139.7865
            note: |
              A single street of over 170 professional kitchenware shops
              — knives, lacquerware, chopsticks, ceramics, and the
              incredible sampuru plastic food displays that fill
              restaurant windows across Japan. 5 minutes' walk
              northwest of Senso-ji.

              Good place to buy a quality Japanese knife (cheaper here
              than in Shinjuku or Ginza), a cast-iron teapot, or a
              proper set of chopsticks to bring home.

              **Cultural note:** Sampuru (food replicas) were invented here in the 1930s,
              originally made from wax. The industry was born from a
              desire to help customers understand menus without pointing
              at pictures — considered awkward in Japanese dining
              culture. Today the most detailed pieces take artisans
              days to make.
        - Hoppy Street and Asakusa backstreets:
            time: 3pm
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [walk, neighbourhood, atmosphere]
            note: |
              Walked the quiet lanes east and north of Senso-ji —
              old wooden shopfronts, small craft studios. Hoppy Street
              for an afternoon drink.
    - day:
        title: Ueno Toshogu, Shinobazu Pond, museum, Akihabara, teamLab
        time: 2026-05-07
        status: done
        note: |
          Morning order changed from plan — started with Ueno Toshogu
          Shrine, then Shinobazu Pond, then Tokyo National Museum.
          Ramen lunch near Ameyoko. Akihabara: Super Potato, game
          arcade, Radio Kaikan, Yodobashi Camera. Went straight to
          teamLab from Akihabara. Late night food from 7-Eleven.
        items:
        - Ueno Toshogu Shrine:
            time: morning
            tags: [shrine, hidden gem, cultural, Edo period]
            location:
              name: Ueno Toshogu Shrine
              lat: 35.7165
              lng: 139.7741
            note: |
              Gold-lacquered Toshogu shrine inside Ueno Park — almost
              no visitors stop here despite it being one of the most
              ornate structures in Tokyo.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1627, rebuilt in gold-leaf form in 1651.
              The 200 stone lanterns were donated by feudal lords from
              across Japan as tribute. Shares the same architectural
              vocabulary as the famous Nikko Toshogu — the same gold
              chrysanthemums, the same carved mythological animals —
              but almost always empty.
        - Shinobazu Pond and Ueno Park:
            tags: [nature, park, walk]
            location:
              name: Shinobazu Pond, Ueno
              lat: 35.7131
              lng: 139.7714
            note: |
              Large lotus pond in the middle of Ueno Park, with a small
              Benten shrine on an island accessed by a narrow causeway.
        - Tokyo National Museum:
            tags: [museum, history, culture]
            location:
              name: Tokyo National Museum
              lat: 35.7189
              lng: 139.7764
            note: |
              Visited the Honkan gallery and Horyuji Treasures Gallery.
              One of the finest rooms of Asian art anywhere in the world.
        - Ramen lunch near Ameyoko:
            tags: [food]
            location:
              name: Ameyoko Market area, Ueno
              lat: 35.7089
              lng: 139.7745
            note: Ramen restaurant near the Ameyoko Market.
        - Akihabara:
            tags: [electronics, pop culture, retro gaming]
            location:
              name: Akihabara Electric Town
              lat: 35.7022
              lng: 139.7742
            note: |
              Super Potato (retro games), game arcade, Radio Kaikan,
              Yodobashi Camera. Went straight to teamLab from here.
        - Transit to teamLab Planets (Toyosu):
            time: 6:30pm
            duration: 25m
            tags: [logistics]
            note: |
              Hibiya Line from Akihabara to Tsukishima, then Yurakucho
              Line one stop to Toyosu.
        - teamLab Planets TOKYO:
            time: 7:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [art, immersive, experience]
            location:
              name: teamLab Planets TOKYO
              lat: 35.6500
              lng: 139.7847
            info:
            - booking: GYG9966Q2V24 (GetYourGuide app)
            - price: 49.92 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              Four large-scale immersive art environments — including
              a room where you wade barefoot through ankle-deep water
              as projected koi scatter when you step, and a garden
              of flowers in infinite bloom. Bring shorts or clothes
              you don't mind getting slightly damp. No shoes inside.

              **Cultural note:** teamLab's art philosophy is rooted in the Japanese
              concept of "ma" — the meaningful space between things.
              The water room works because you cannot pass through
              it without affecting it, and the koi cannot exist without
              your presence disturbing them. The relationship between
              visitor and artwork is genuinely reciprocal.
    - day:
        title: Ameyoko eel lunch, Odaiba, Fuji TV, Gundam, Skytree sunset
        time: 2026-05-08
        status: done
        note: |
          Lunch at Ameyoko Market — eel BBQ restaurant. Then Yurikamome
          to Odaiba: Fuji TV building exterior, DiverCity and Gundam
          statue. Tokyo Skytree — browsed Solamachi stores on floor 4,
          then Tembo Deck for sunset views. Late dinner at Hoppy Street
          in Asakusa.
        items:
        - Eel BBQ lunch at Ameyoko Market:
            tags: [food, market]
            location:
              name: Ameyoko Market, Ueno
              lat: 35.7089
              lng: 139.7745
            note: Restaurant specialising in eel BBQ inside the Ameyoko Market area.
        - Yurikamome monorail to Odaiba:
            tags: [transport, experience]
            location:
              name: Shimbashi Station (Yurikamome Line)
              lat: 35.6659
              lng: 139.7576
            note: Driverless elevated monorail crossing Tokyo Bay over the Rainbow Bridge.
        - Fuji TV Building:
            tags: [architecture, landmark]
            location:
              name: Fuji TV Building, Odaiba
              lat: 35.6290
              lng: 139.7768
            note: |
              The distinctive sphere suspended between two towers —
              one of Japan's most recognisable pieces of 1990s
              architectural confidence. Viewed from the waterfront.
        - Gundam statue and DiverCity:
            tags: [pop culture, experience]
            location:
              name: DiverCity Tokyo Plaza
              lat: 35.6249
              lng: 139.7756
            note: Life-size Gundam mobile suit in front of DiverCity mall.
        - Tokyo Skytree — Solamachi and Tembo Deck:
            tags: [viewpoint, landmark, shopping]
            location:
              name: Tokyo Skytree
              lat: 35.7101
              lng: 139.8107
            info:
            - booking: GYGBLHRMGF63 (GetYourGuide app)
            - price: 19.54 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              Browsed stores on floor 4 of Solamachi, then Tembo Deck
              at 350m for sunset views over Tokyo.
        - Late dinner at Hoppy Street:
            tags: [food, izakaya, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Hoppy Street, Asakusa
              lat: 35.7134
              lng: 139.7954
            note: Casual yakitori izakaya on Hoppy Street in Asakusa.
    - day:
        title: Shinjuku — 3D cat, Godzilla, TMG, Kinokuniya, Memory Lane dinner
        time: 2026-05-09
        status: done
        note: |
          3D cat billboard at Shinjuku East exit, then Godzilla statue
          on Toho Building street. TMG Building — elevator under
          maintenance, couldn't go up. Curry lunch in Kabukicho.
          Walked the main street, browsed Kinokuniya bookshop. Headed
          toward Shinjuku Gyoen but didn't enter. Hanazono Shrine.
          Golden Gai — arrived too early, all closed. Finished at
          Omoide Yokocho — dinner at a tiny yakitori BBQ restaurant.
        items:
        - 3D cat billboard:
            tags: [landmark, street art]
            location:
              name: Shinjuku East Exit
              lat: 35.6912
              lng: 139.7025
            note: The enormous 3D cat screen at the Shinjuku East exit.
        - Godzilla statue — Toho Building:
            tags: [pop culture, landmark]
            location:
              name: Toho Building, Kabukicho
              lat: 35.6948
              lng: 139.7025
            note: Godzilla head on the Toho Building roof. Walked the Kabukicho street.
        - Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building:
            tags: [architecture, landmark]
            location:
              name: Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building
              lat: 35.6895
              lng: 139.6917
            note: Visited but elevator was under maintenance — couldn't access the observation deck.
        - Curry lunch in Kabukicho:
            tags: [food]
            note: Lunch at a curry restaurant in the Kabukicho area.
        - Kinokuniya Bookshop:
            tags: [bookshop, culture]
            location:
              name: Kinokuniya Shinjuku
              lat: 35.6929
              lng: 139.7024
            note: Browsed the large Kinokuniya bookshop on the main street.
        - Toward Shinjuku Gyoen (didn't enter):
            tags: [walk]
            note: Walked in the direction of the park but didn't go in.
        - Hanazono Shrine:
            tags: [shrine, atmosphere]
            location:
              name: Hanazono Shrine
              lat: 35.6937
              lng: 139.7072
            note: |
              Compact Shinto shrine in Kabukicho — stone lanterns and
              the main hall, a moment of quiet inside the entertainment
              district.
        - Golden Gai (closed — too early):
            tags: [nightlife]
            location:
              name: Golden Gai
              lat: 35.6943
              lng: 139.7035
            note: Arrived too early — all bars were still closed.
        - Omoide Yokocho dinner:
            tags: [food, izakaya, atmosphere]
            location:
              name: Omoide Yokocho
              lat: 35.6939
              lng: 139.7006
            note: |
              Dinner at a tiny yakitori BBQ restaurant on Memory Lane
              — charcoal grills, paper lanterns, skewers at the counter.
    - day:
        title: Rest day — cafe, Sushiro, Akihabara shopping, Yanaka Ginza
        time: 2026-05-11
        status: done
        note: |
          Mount Takao skipped — took a lighter rest day instead.
          Breakfast at a cafe near the hotel. Lunch at Sushiro conveyor
          belt sushi near Nippori Station. Akihabara for shopping at
          Yodobashi Camera. Yanaka Ginza at sunset for beer and sake.
          Dinner at the hotel restaurant — udon.
        items:
        - Breakfast at cafe near hotel:
            tags: [food, slow morning]
            note: Slow breakfast at a local cafe near Sakura Hotel Nippori.
        - Sushiro lunch:
            tags: [food, sushi]
            location:
              name: Sushiro near Nippori Station
              lat: 35.7283
              lng: 139.7700
            note: Conveyor belt sushi lunch near Nippori Station.
        - Akihabara — Yodobashi Camera shopping:
            tags: [shopping, electronics]
            location:
              name: Akihabara Electric Town
              lat: 35.7022
              lng: 139.7742
            note: Shopping at Yodobashi Camera.
        - Yanaka Ginza at sunset:
            tags: [neighbourhood, drinks, sunset]
            location:
              name: Yanaka Ginza
              lat: 35.7243
              lng: 139.7670
            note: Beer and sake in Yanaka Ginza at sunset.
        - Dinner at hotel restaurant:
            tags: [food]
            note: Udon at the Sakura Hotel Nippori restaurant.

    - day:
        title: Meiji Shrine, Harajuku, Omotesando, Shibuya Crossing from Starbucks
        time: 2026-05-10
        status: done
        note: |
          Meiji Shrine, Yoyogi Park (no rockabilly group that day).
          Lunch at The Beetle in Harajuku. Takeshita Street, then
          backstreets east of Takeshita. Walked through Omotesando
          and Aoyama toward Shibuya. Watched the Scramble Crossing
          from Starbucks 2F (free). Back to hotel, dinner at Kitsune
          Sushi. Skipped: Daikanyama, Nakameguro, Nezu Museum, Shibuya Sky.
        items:
        - Meiji Jingu Shrine:
            time: 7:30am
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [shrine, nature, spiritual]
            location:
              name: Meiji Jingu Shrine
              lat: 35.6763
              lng: 139.6993
            note: |
              Arrive at 7:30am. The inner garden (irises in bloom
              in May) costs 500 yen and is deeply worth it.

              A Shinto shrine set within 70 hectares of forested
              grounds in the heart of the city — the 700m forested
              approach of zelkova and camphor trees is extraordinary
              at dawn, before tour groups arrive.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1920 to honour Emperor Meiji (1852-1912) and
              Empress Shoken — the rulers who oversaw Japan's
              transformation from feudal isolation to industrialised
              world power. The 100,000 trees were donated by people
              from across Japan and Taiwan, chosen to create a
              self-sustaining forest ecosystem designed to last
              1,000 years. On weekend mornings Shinto weddings
              process through the inner courtyard in silence.

        - Yoyogi Park:
            time: 9am
            duration: 30m
            tags: [park, nature, local]
            note: |
              54 hectares of public park adjacent to Meiji Shrine —
              open forest, wide lawns, and on weekends an
              extraordinary parade of subcultures near the west gate.

              **Cultural note:** Look for the rockabilly groups near the Harajuku Gate
              — men in elaborate 1950s American hairstyles dancing
              to early rock and roll. They have gathered here weekly
              since the early 1980s. The juxtaposition of this
              American nostalgia culture directly beside Japan's most
              sacred imperial shrine is uniquely, inexplicably Tokyo.
        - Takeshita Street, Harajuku:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h
            tags: [youth culture, shopping, street]
            location:
              name: Takeshita Street
              lat: 35.6715
              lng: 139.7042
            note: |
              A 350m pedestrian street of youth fashion boutiques,
              crepe stands, and costume shops — the physical home
              of Harajuku fashion culture.

              **Cultural note:** Harajuku's extreme fashion culture emerged in the 1980s
              partly as acceptable rebellion against Japan's rigid
              corporate conformity. Wearing a costume in public is
              tolerated here in a way it would not be elsewhere —
              the street itself acts as a designated permission space.
              The elaborate layered crepes (French style, Japanese
              execution) were invented here and remain excellent.
        - Omotesando Avenue:
            time: 11am
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [architecture, walk, design]
            note: |
              A tree-lined boulevard of flagship stores notable for
              their architecture — Prada (Herzog and de Meuron,
              crystal lattice facade), Tod's (Toyo Ito, tree-branching
              concrete) — world-class architects commissioned for
              retail units.

              **Cultural note:** The zelkova trees lining Omotesando were planted in
              the 1920s for the Meiji Shrine dedication and are
              legally protected. When threatened during 2020 Olympics
              preparations, a significant public campaign protected
              them. The Nezu Museum at the south end has a beautiful
              traditional garden (1,500 yen).
        - Nezu Museum and garden:
            time: 12:30pm
            duration: 45m
            tags: [museum, garden, traditional, hidden gem]
            location:
              name: Nezu Museum
              lat: 35.6641
              lng: 139.7152
            note: |
              At the south end of Omotesando — a private museum of
              Asian decorative art with one of Tokyo's finest
              traditional gardens behind it. The garden is the point:
              stone lanterns, a tea house, koi ponds, and a dense
              bamboo grove that feels completely detached from the
              boulevard 50 metres away. Entry ¥1,500.

              **Cultural note:** The collection was assembled by Nezu Kaichiro (1860-1940),
              founder of Tobu Railway, over 40 years — over 7,000
              objects spanning Japan, China, and Korea. The garden
              is designed in the traditional strolling style (kaiyushiki),
              meaning it reveals itself gradually as you walk rather
              than presenting a single view from a fixed point. The
              contrast between Omotesando's deliberate spectacle and
              this garden's deliberate concealment is worth pausing
              on.
        - Lunch near Omotesando or Aoyama:
            time: 1:30pm
            tags: [food]
            note: |
              The Aoyama neighbourhood behind Omotesando has quiet,
              high-quality restaurants without the boulevard pricing.
              A Japanese curry (kare) lunch set is one of Tokyo's
              great comfort foods — filling, inexpensive, and rarely
              disappointing.
        - Daikanyama and T-Site Tsutaya:
            time: 2:30pm
            duration: 1h
            tags: [neighbourhood, bookshop, walk]
            note: |
              Tokyo's quietest sophisticated neighbourhood — a maze
              of low buildings, select shops, and excellent cafes,
              anchored by the Daikanyama T-Site Tsutaya (flagship
              bookshop and design store set in wooded grounds).

              **Cultural note:** T-Site was designed by Klein Dytham Architecture (2011)
              and is considered one of the world's most beautiful
              bookshops. The building is clad in repeating letter T
              pattern — what appears abstract is thousands of
              overlapping Ts. The shop stocks vinyl records, art
              books, and design objects alongside books.
        - Nakameguro canal walk:
            time: 3:30pm
            duration: 45m
            tags: [walk, canal, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Nakameguro Canal
              lat: 35.6419
              lng: 139.6992
            note: |
              A 10-minute walk downhill from Daikanyama brings you
              to the Meguro River canal — walk the 1.5km north along
              the water toward Shibuya, passing small independent
              cafes, bakeries, and boutiques under overhanging trees.
              This is the unhurried transition between Daikanyama's
              calm and Shibuya's energy, and one of the most pleasant
              30-minute walks in Tokyo.

              **Cultural note:** The canal was built in the Meiji era for flood
              control and irrigation — utterly functional, entirely
              unplanned as a destination. Its transformation into
              Tokyo's most desirable strolling district happened
              organically from the 1990s onward as small creative
              businesses filled the low-rent buildings along the
              water. In June the leaves are dense and green; in spring
              the cherry trees that line it produce Tokyo's most
              beautiful hanami scene.
        - Shibuya Sky — rooftop observation:
            time: 5:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [viewpoint, experience]
            location:
              name: Shibuya Sky, Shibuya Scramble Square
              lat: 35.6590
              lng: 139.7025
            note: |
              An open-air rooftop on top of Shibuya Scramble Square
              — 360° views at the hour the city lights up and the
              Scramble Crossing below enters its peak chaos. Book
              online in advance (¥2,000).

              From up here the crossing looks like a single organism
              — 2,500 people moving in every direction simultaneously,
              organising themselves without collision. Then go down
              and be part of it.
        - Shibuya Scramble Crossing on foot:
            time: 6:30pm
            duration: 20m
            tags: [landmark, experience, cultural]
            location:
              name: Shibuya Scramble Crossing
              lat: 35.6595
              lng: 139.7004
            note: |
              Cross it. The experience from street level — surrounded
              by thousands of people moving in every direction, neon
              signs igniting above, the organised chaos that somehow
              works — is completely different from watching it from
              the rooftop. Cross several times from different corners.

              **Cultural note:** The scramble system (all signals red simultaneously)
              was implemented because the intersection had become too
              busy to manage with standard crossings. It is now a
              globally recognised image of urban Japan — not because
              it was designed to be, but because it accidentally
              became the most visible expression of how Tokyo actually
              functions: dense, precise, and strangely calm.
        - Dinner in Shibuya:
            time: 7pm
            tags: [food]
            note: |
              Shibuya has excellent options in every direction from
              the crossing. The Udagawacho backstreets northwest of
              the station have independent restaurants without the
              tourist pricing of the main drags. Or head to Log Road
              Daikanyama (a 15-min walk back) for a calmer setting
              after the crossing's energy.


    - day:
        title: Checkout, Romancecar to Hakone, explore Yumoto
        time: 2026-05-12
        status: done
        items:
        - Checkout and bag handling:
            time: 11am
            note: |
              Consider TA-Q-BIN forwarding — send bags directly
              to Bansuirou Fukuzumi the night before (ryokan accepts
              from 3pm same day). Or store at Shinjuku Station
              coin lockers.

        - Shinjuku depachika browsing:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h
            note: |
              Final Tokyo morning. Browse B1-B2 of Takashimaya or
              Odakyu. Buy a light lunch for the train, or eat at a
              standing noodle shop in the station concourse.

        - Romancecar Hakone 25:
            time: 12:20pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h27m
            tags: [train, experience]
            location:
              name: Shinjuku Station — Odakyu Romancecar Platform
              lat: 35.6896
              lng: 139.7006
            info:
            - train: Romancecar Hakone 25
            - departs: 12:20 from Shinjuku
            - arrives: 13:47 at Hakone Yumoto
            - car: "4"
            - seats: 5D (Bruna) and 5C (Renan)
            - booking: CHS832036 (Klook)
            - price: 14.08 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              A premium reserved-seat express with panoramic windows,
              running direct from Shinjuku to Hakone Yumoto without
              stopping. The last 30 minutes wind through forested
              mountain river valley.

              **Cultural note:** The Romancecar (named since 1957) was designed as an
              escape train — the idea that a couple could board in
              the city and arrive somewhere deeply different in under
              90 minutes was considered romantic and modern. It still
              works. Show the Klook confirmation and Hakone Freepass
              at the platform gate.
        - Explore Hakone Yumoto:
            tags: [walk, neighbourhood, nature]
            location:
              name: Hakone Yumoto
              lat: 35.2350
              lng: 139.1050
            note: |
              Walked the shops along the main street, the Hayakawa
              River, and discovered a small waterfall near a shrine.
        - Check in and dinner at Bansuirou Fukuzumi:
            tags: [ryokan, onsen, food]
            note: Checked in to the ryokan and had dinner there.
- Hakone:
    arrives: 2026-05-12T13:47
    departs: 2026-05-14
    duration: 2 nights
    location: Hakone, Kanagawa, Japan
    tags: [onsen, nature, ryokan, mountain, volcanic, Fuji]
    stay:
    - Bansuirou Fukuzumi:
        arrives: 2026-05-12T16:00
        departs: 2026-05-14T09:00
        location:
          address: 250-0311, Hakone, Kanagawa, Japan
          lat: 35.2333
          lng: 139.1000
        info:
        - confirmation: "5549903534"
        - pin: "9274"
        - phone: 81460855531
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Japanese-Style Superior Room B — Private Hot Spring Bath and River View
        - price: 112,000 yen — payment scheduled May 7 (card ending 6075)
        note: |
          A ryokan with a private outdoor rotenburo (hot spring bath)
          overlooking the river. Kaiseki meals served in-room or in
          private dining. Mention seafood preference when confirming
          so the kitchen can adjust the courses.
    info:
    - Hakone-Freepass:
        first-day: 2026-05-12
        control: "2965129"
        price: 6,400 yen — already paid
        note: Verify whether second pass for Renan was purchased.
        covers: |
          Hakone Tozan Railway, Tozan Cable Car (Gora-Sounzan),
          Hakone Ropeway (Sounzan-Togendai via Owakudani),
          Lake Ashi Sightseeing Cruise, Tozan Bus, Izu-Hakone Bus.
          Does NOT cover Romancecar or Shinkansen.
        how-to-use: EMot app — www.emot-tickets.jp/my-tickets
    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival afternoon — walked Yumoto, checked in, ryokan dinner
        time: 2026-05-12
        status: done
        items:
        - Hakone Tozan Railway to Chokoku-no-Mori:
            time: 2pm
            tags: [train, experience]
            note: |
              Store bags at Yumoto Station coin lockers or arrange ryokan pickup first.

              Japan's steepest mountain railway, using a switchback
              system where the train reverses direction three times
              to climb the gradient. The forested hillsides are
              dense and green in May.

              **Cultural note:** The Hakone Tozan Railway (1919) was built partly to
              serve the ryokan industry. The hydrangeas planted
              along the tracks over decades bloom in mid-June into
              a wall of blue and purple visible from the windows.


        - Hakone Open-Air Museum:
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [art, outdoor, sculpture]
            location:
              name: Hakone Open-Air Museum
              lat: 35.2397
              lng: 139.0472
            note: |
              A hillside museum displaying sculptures by Henry Moore,
              Rodin, Miro, Calder, and others across manicured lawn
              terraces with the Hakone mountains as backdrop. The
              Picasso Pavilion holds over 300 works.

              **Cultural note:** Japan's first outdoor museum (1969), conceived by art
              critic Kiichiro Shimizu, who believed art should exist
              in nature rather than be imprisoned in white-walled
              galleries. The outdoor footbath (ashiyu) at the museum
              is free for visitors — soak your feet in naturally
              flowing volcanic spring water while looking at sculpture.
        - Check in and first rotenburo:
            time: 4pm
            note: |
              Change into yukata (provided). Use the private rotenburo
              before dinner. This is the experience — naturally
              flowing hot spring water in a private outdoor bath above
              a mountain river, in a traditional inn. Take your time.

        - Kaiseki dinner:
            time: evening
            tags: [food, experience]
            note: |
              A multi-course seasonal meal of Kyoto-influenced Japanese
              haute cuisine — each small course beautifully presented,
              using mountain vegetables, tofu, and local ingredients.

              **Cultural note:** Kaiseki originated in the Zen tea ceremony tradition —
              light food served before a tea ceremony to prevent
              drinking matcha on an empty stomach. It evolved into
              Japan's most refined culinary form over 400 years.
    - day:
        title: The Hakone Loop — ropeway, volcano, Lake Ashi
        time: 2026-05-13
        status: done
        note: |
          Full loop completed as planned: Tozan Railway, Cable Car,
          Ropeway, Owakudani, Lake Ashi cruise, Hakone Shrine.
          Partial Fuji visibility — cloudy with some clearing.
          Lunch was 7-Eleven sandwiches eaten by the lakeside before
          visiting the shrine (not after). Final rotenburo and kaiseki
          at the ryokan in the evening.
        items:
        - Breakfast at the ryokan:
            time: morning
            note: Traditional Japanese breakfast — miso soup, grilled vegetables, tamagoyaki, rice, pickles. Politely 
              decline the fish if needed.

        - Tozan Railway, then cable car, then ropeway:
            time: 9am
            tags: [transport, experience]
            note: "Route: Yumoto > (Tozan) > Gora > (Cable Car) > Sounzan > (Ropeway) > Owakudani > (Ropeway continues) >
              Togendai"

        - Owakudani Volcanic Valley:
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [nature, volcanic, experience]
            location:
              name: Owakudani
              lat: 35.2553
              lng: 139.0225
            note: |
              An active volcanic crater at 1,044m — steaming
              fumaroles, sulphur vents, boiling mud pools, and the
              famous kuro tamago (black eggs boiled in volcanic
              springs, said to add 7 years to your life).

              **Cultural note:** The valley was formed 3,000 years ago by a volcanic
              eruption of Mount Hakone. "Owakudani" means "great
              boiling valley." The eggs turn black because iron
              sulphide in the springs reacts with hydrogen sulphide
              gas coating the shell. On a clear day from here, Mount
              Fuji rises over the ridge to the north — one of the
              most dramatic views in Japan.
        - Lake Ashi Sightseeing Cruise:
            priority: must
            duration: 35m
            tags: [boat, lake, scenic]
            location:
              name: Lake Ashi (Ashino-ko)
              lat: 35.2040
              lng: 139.0260
            note: |
              A cruise across the volcanic caldera lake on one of
              the pirate-galleon-style ships, from Togendai at the
              north shore to Moto-Hakone or Hakone-machi at the south.

              **Cultural note:** Lake Ashi formed inside the caldera of Mount Hakone.
              The lake has no outflowing river — all water drains
              underground through volcanic rock. On perfectly still
              mornings, Mount Fuji's reflection appears complete in
              the water surface. The pirate ships are a tourism
              conceit from the 1960s and oddly charming.
        - Hakone Shrine:
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [shrine, nature, cultural]
            location:
              name: Hakone Shrine
              lat: 35.1981
              lng: 139.0273
            note: |
              A Shinto shrine in ancient cedar forest at the southern
              edge of Lake Ashi — famous for its vermilion torii gate
              standing in the water, approached via a long forested
              avenue.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 757 AD by the monk Mangan. The lakeside torii
              marks the water entrance to the shrine — in the Shinto
              tradition, entering from water is the purified approach.
              Very quiet, very old. One of the most beautiful short
              walks in the Hakone area.
        - Lunch in Moto-Hakone and return by bus:
            time: midday
            note: |
              Several restaurants on the lakefront. Look for soba —
              Hakone is in buckwheat country. Return by Odakyu
              Highway Bus (Freepass) to Hakone Yumoto.

        - Final onsen and farewell kaiseki:
            time: evening
            note: |
              Last night in the ryokan. Use the private rotenburo
              again — the experience is different at night. A good
              moment to try the ryokan's sake selection.

    - day:
        title: Checkout, then to Osaka
        time: 2026-05-14
        items:
        - Breakfast and checkout:
            time: 8am
            note: Checkout 08:00-10:00. Depart for Odawara.
        - Travel to Osaka:
            note: |
              Hakone Yumoto > Odawara by Tozan train (~13 min).
              Odawara > Shin-Osaka by Nozomi Shinkansen (~1h).
              Book via Smart EX. Freepass does not cover this leg.

